<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-03-08T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-03-08T17:00:00-05:00" n="506" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d506">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/4027: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DJW1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-03-08T17:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">March 8,
                                        1919, 5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>4772. In connection with instructions to Consul-General <persName corresp="#p_HEL1">Harris</persName> in Siberia, the text of which
                            was telegraphed to you today, if you see no objection, please read to
                            Foreign Office following cable from American Consul at Vladivostok. You
                            should now have received a personal letter from me<note n="29" xml:id="d506fn29">Not printed.</note> which also bears on this
                            subject and should throw additional light on it.</p>
                        <p>[Here follows text of telegram 106, March 3, 3 p.m., from the Consul at
                            Vladivostok, printed <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_473">page 473</ref>.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_PFL"><hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>